# Feature Overview

## Automated Project Tracker

Automated Project Tracker is a macro-enabled Excel workbook designed to help users organize projects, track tasks, manage notes, and record release progress in one reusable file.

The workbook was built for people who want a practical project management tool without needing a subscription, login, or complex software setup.

---

## Core Features

### Project Dashboard

The dashboard gives users a central place to view and manage their projects.

Key dashboard features include:

- Project overview area
- Current project list
- Project status tracking
- Quick access to project workspaces
- Clean layout designed for simple navigation

The goal of the dashboard is to help users quickly see what they are working on and move into the project they need.

---

### New Project Creation

The workbook includes an automated workflow for creating new projects.

Users can create a project from the dashboard, and the workbook generates a dedicated project workspace based on the project tracker layout.

This helps keep each project organized without requiring the user to manually copy, rename, or rebuild sheets.

---

### Project Workspace

Each project workspace is designed to hold the main information needed to manage a project from start to finish.

The project workspace includes areas for:

- Project details
- Task tracking
- Project notes
- Brainstorming
- Release notes
- Version/release tracking

This gives each project its own organized space while keeping the overall workbook structure consistent.

---

### Task Tracking

The task tracking section helps users break project work into smaller action items.

Users can track task details such as:

- Task name
- Category or phase
- Status
- Priority
- Notes
- Progress

This section is designed to help users see what needs to be done, what is currently in progress, and what has already been completed.

---

### Notes and Brainstorming

The workbook includes dedicated areas for project notes and brainstorming.

These sections are useful for:

- Capturing ideas
- Writing reminders
- Planning future updates
- Recording decisions
- Keeping project context in one place

The goal is to reduce scattered notes and keep project-related thinking inside the workbook.

---

### Release and Version Tracking

Automated Project Tracker includes a release/version tracking workflow.

This allows users to track:

- Completed versions
- Release names
- Release dates
- Release notes
- Previous release history

This is especially useful for creators, developers, spreadsheet builders, app builders, or anyone working through multiple versions of a project.

---

### Project Logs

The workbook includes logging areas so users can keep a record of project activity and progress over time.

Logs can help users look back at:

- Older notes
- Past updates
- Completed work
- Version history
- Project decisions

This makes the workbook useful not only for planning, but also for reviewing progress after work has been completed.

---

### Beginner-Friendly Workflow

The workbook was designed to be usable by people who do not write code.

Although it uses Excel automation and VBA behind the scenes, the user interacts with buttons, structured sections, and guided workbook areas.

The focus is on making the workbook feel like a simple project app inside Excel.

---

## Built With

This project was built using:

- Microsoft Excel
- VBA automation
- Excel tables
- Form-style layouts
- Dashboard design
- Macro-enabled workbook structure
- Digital product packaging

---

## Design Goals

The main goals of this workbook were to create a tool that is:

- Practical
- Reusable
- Easy to understand
- Organized
- Helpful for real project work
- More powerful than a basic spreadsheet
- Simpler than full project management software

Automated Project Tracker was built as a lightweight productivity tool for users who want structure without unnecessary complexity.

